WEBVTT

00:05.306 --> 00:06.572
SAM:
<i> Previously on</i> Aquarius...

00:06.574 --> 00:10.309
Use of deadly force,
unlawful discharge
of weapon,

00:10.311 --> 00:11.443
lying under oath.

00:11.445 --> 00:12.678
You can walk down quietly,

00:12.680 --> 00:15.114
or you can take
a long, loud fall.

00:15.116 --> 00:15.614
(GASPS)

00:15.616 --> 00:17.916
Your buddy, the cop?
Bri? Give him up...

00:17.918 --> 00:20.252
Yeah. He's yours.
He's completely yours.

00:20.254 --> 00:22.187
Put me on Vice.
I'll be a honey trap.
Anything.

00:22.189 --> 00:24.189
Just do not send me
back to the desk.

00:24.191 --> 00:25.024
You should've
thought of that

00:25.026 --> 00:26.959
before you burned
your CI to your boyfriend.

00:26.961 --> 00:29.028
Well, I hope Hodiak's
your boyfriend.

00:29.030 --> 00:31.530
Considering how he royally
screwed up your career.

00:31.532 --> 00:33.298
I want to go
to Spahn Ranch.

00:33.300 --> 00:36.735
Nothing but play
for miles and miles.

00:36.737 --> 00:37.569
SADIE: <i> I know where we can go.</i>

00:37.571 --> 00:38.704
<i> Hal said there's</i>
<i> an old movie ranch?</i>

00:38.706 --> 00:41.707
<i> There's nobody there.</i>
<i> We could just</i>
<i> go there and crash.</i>

00:41.709 --> 00:43.542
You, Sam,
are addicted

00:43.544 --> 00:45.110
Not to being a cop.

00:45.112 --> 00:46.545
To solving a mystery.

00:46.547 --> 00:47.212
You're moving out?

00:47.214 --> 00:49.548
KRISTIN:
You're a part of something...

00:49.550 --> 00:51.650
It's bent on keeping me down.

00:51.652 --> 00:54.086
I can't live with the enemy.

01:15.543 --> 01:17.042
(GUNSHOT)

01:58.986 --> 02:01.854
(PHONE RINGS)
(LINE CLICKS)

02:01.856 --> 02:02.788
KRISTIN: (OVER PHONE) <i> Hey.</i>

02:02.790 --> 02:05.891
BRIAN: Baby, I'm lonely.
KRISTIN: <i> Uh-huh.</i>

02:06.127 --> 02:07.659
I've gone feral.

02:07.661 --> 02:09.027
Too much time alone.

02:09.029 --> 02:12.698
Krissy, it's been
four months. Come home.

02:13.234 --> 02:15.968
<i> Well, nothing's changed,</i>
<i> has it?</i>

02:16.370 --> 02:18.137
I want to see Bernadette.

02:18.139 --> 02:19.304
(CLANKS)

02:19.306 --> 02:21.073
<i> Then come see her.</i>

02:21.075 --> 02:22.274
That's hard to do without

02:22.276 --> 02:23.942
punching your
old man in the face.

02:23.944 --> 02:26.245
<i> You don't have to be</i>
<i> the bigger man, Bri,</i>

02:26.247 --> 02:27.980
<i> but you have to admit that</i>
<i> we have problems</i>

02:27.982 --> 02:29.748
<i> that aren't going away.</i>

02:29.750 --> 02:33.118
Are you through with me?
Say it.

02:39.460 --> 02:41.393
<i> I'll call tomorrow.</i>

02:42.096 --> 02:43.695
(KNIFE CLATTERS)

03:07.188 --> 03:08.987
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

03:08.989 --> 03:10.289
CUT: Where you been?

03:10.291 --> 03:11.223
My car was stolen.

03:11.225 --> 03:13.492
That's very funny.
And yet not.

03:13.494 --> 03:14.593
You listen
to the radio?

03:14.595 --> 03:17.396
The radio that was
in the car that was stolen?

03:17.665 --> 03:19.364
Commissioner resigned.

03:20.434 --> 03:21.600
He say why?
No.

03:21.602 --> 03:25.971
But if I had to guess,
had something to do with you.

03:28.075 --> 03:29.775
Commissioner Garrick resigned

03:29.777 --> 03:32.211
because of allegations
of gross misconduct,

03:32.213 --> 03:33.779
including the mishandling

03:33.781 --> 03:36.782
of officer investigations,
including yours.

03:37.051 --> 03:37.516
So, the mayor

03:37.518 --> 03:40.419
has appointed Robert Culpepper
as the interim commissioner.

03:40.421 --> 03:45.290
(SIGHS) Culpepper, the former
head of IA, your old boss?

03:45.292 --> 03:47.492
Who Garrick
pushed out.

03:47.561 --> 03:48.894
(SCOFFS)

03:49.930 --> 03:52.030
You arranged this.

03:52.132 --> 03:53.765
You wanted Garrick
to end my investigation

03:53.767 --> 03:56.501
so you could call it a
scandal and hang him with it.

03:56.503 --> 03:58.737
Some things
are happy accidents.

03:58.739 --> 04:01.740
But most things?
They take work.

04:02.710 --> 04:03.709
Detective Hodiak,

04:03.711 --> 04:06.278
you're suspended
until further notice.

04:06.280 --> 04:07.980
Thank you, gentlemen.

04:08.482 --> 04:11.149
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

04:21.362 --> 04:23.028
EMMA: Morning, Daddy.

04:24.331 --> 04:25.697
KEN: Emma.

04:26.100 --> 04:28.300
I was just...
Don't explain.

04:28.302 --> 04:31.336
When I first met Charlie,

04:31.872 --> 04:35.741
it was like everything
I was scared of was gone.

04:36.043 --> 04:38.877
Everything I did
was right.

04:39.513 --> 04:41.246
I was weightless.

04:43.017 --> 04:47.919
I don't feel weightless.
I feel old.

04:48.155 --> 04:50.389
All the time I wasted.

04:51.358 --> 04:53.025
EMMA: Not one more

04:53.027 --> 04:55.360
second than you had to,
to become what you are.

04:56.163 --> 04:58.830
(LAUGHS) I don't know
what that means.

04:58.832 --> 05:00.032
Neither do I.

05:00.034 --> 05:03.802
It's something Charlie says,
but it feels true.

05:04.905 --> 05:06.071
Where is Charlie?

05:06.073 --> 05:06.972
He's taking a nap.

05:06.974 --> 05:09.641
He was out all night
searching for the hole.

05:09.643 --> 05:10.942
"The hole"?

05:10.944 --> 05:12.077
In the desert.

05:12.079 --> 05:14.780
Where we're gonna hide
when things get bad.

05:14.782 --> 05:16.581
I was just about
to bring him some food.

05:16.583 --> 05:18.250
There's food?
The girls got back?

05:18.252 --> 05:20.452
Not yet. We had
some hidden, though.

05:20.454 --> 05:21.720
Charlie's been having us bury

05:21.722 --> 05:23.822
half of everything
we bring back.

05:24.458 --> 05:25.824
For what?

05:28.696 --> 05:30.462
MINNIE: Charlie!

05:33.834 --> 05:37.536
Charlie, we need you!
Charlie!

05:38.539 --> 05:41.473
Charlie. (PANTING)
We need you.

05:42.142 --> 05:44.242
Mary, what's wrong?

05:44.678 --> 05:46.378
(SOBBING) Charlie.

05:48.682 --> 05:51.717
They took him, Charlie.
They took our baby.

05:51.719 --> 05:54.653
They took Valentine.
I'm sorry.

05:54.655 --> 05:56.922
What happened?
We were supposed
to be using your card

05:56.924 --> 05:58.657
to get supplies...
But it didn't work...

05:58.659 --> 06:01.693
So they cut up the card
and they threw us out.

06:01.695 --> 06:04.229
MINNIE: There was nothing
left in the dumpster,

06:04.231 --> 06:07.332
so we had to beg,
and the cops saw us.

06:07.334 --> 06:10.702
They said, they said
it's no place for a baby.

06:12.406 --> 06:13.905
I'm sorry.

06:16.343 --> 06:17.676
MINNIE: Charlie.

06:17.678 --> 06:19.311
This is on you, Ken.

06:19.580 --> 06:21.079
Easy.
"Easy"?

06:21.081 --> 06:23.982
Those pigs took my child.

06:23.984 --> 06:25.517
And you took mine.

06:26.186 --> 06:28.387
So, put the knife down.

06:29.623 --> 06:31.423
And let me help you.

06:40.701 --> 06:42.634
DETECTIVE SCHLATKE:
Make and model?

06:43.303 --> 06:45.704
Uh, '67 Plymouth Belvedere.

06:45.706 --> 06:47.172
Color?

06:47.775 --> 06:50.375
Kind of a snot green.

06:50.577 --> 06:51.843
You want it back?
Yeah,

06:51.845 --> 06:53.545
I left your sister
in the backseat,

06:53.547 --> 06:54.379
so I would like it back.

06:54.381 --> 06:57.182
Any other valuables
in the car? Your purse, maybe?

06:57.184 --> 06:58.250
(CHUCKLES) If you do find it,

06:58.252 --> 06:59.251
I'm gonna run you
over with it.

06:59.253 --> 07:01.520
I'm not worried,
we probably won't.

07:01.622 --> 07:03.455
(SAM CHUCKLES)

07:08.962 --> 07:10.295
(CHUCKLES)

07:11.198 --> 07:12.798
(SAM LAUGHING)

07:12.800 --> 07:13.832
What?
Don't stop.

07:13.834 --> 07:16.601
It's too good, whatever it is
you're doing, just continue.

07:16.603 --> 07:19.171
Guy asked for tea.
Who are you, Miss Manners?

07:19.173 --> 07:20.906
What are you doing?

07:22.743 --> 07:23.275
Come here.

07:23.277 --> 07:24.643
Don't you have
something better to do?

07:24.645 --> 07:26.178
You got the bag,
you don't...

07:26.180 --> 07:29.014
Oh, right.
You got suspended.

07:30.684 --> 07:32.918
Well, don't you
make it look easy.

07:33.420 --> 07:35.420
Jap bastard probably
won't even drink it.

07:35.422 --> 07:38.223
Your suspect's a Jap?
Yeah.

07:38.225 --> 07:40.325
He got in a fight
with a white guy

07:40.327 --> 07:42.093
while he was
filling up his gas.

07:42.095 --> 07:43.929
(SPITTING)
White guy's dead.

07:43.931 --> 07:45.096
None of the witnesses...

07:45.098 --> 07:47.833
(CLEARS THROAT)
Saw the first punch.

07:49.470 --> 07:51.069
You need some help?

07:52.406 --> 07:53.972
(DOOR OPENS)

07:54.041 --> 07:58.143
Satoshi, I'm Detective Lyons.
This is Detective Hodiak.

07:58.946 --> 08:02.147
If your tea stinks,
he made it.

08:02.716 --> 08:04.983
Okay, so,
you're at the filling station.

08:04.985 --> 08:05.917
You see a man...

08:05.919 --> 08:10.021
He saw me. And then
he attacked me for no reason.

08:10.023 --> 08:11.656
I defended myself.

08:11.658 --> 08:12.958
But you did more than that.

08:12.960 --> 08:14.659
You did more
than defend yourself.

08:14.661 --> 08:15.594
You cracked his head open

08:15.596 --> 08:17.529
on the concrete.
You killed him.

08:17.731 --> 08:22.400
That sounds personal to me,
like, maybe you knew him.

08:22.402 --> 08:23.802
No.
He was a stranger.

08:23.804 --> 08:26.004
You want to see a picture?
Maybe jog your memory?

08:26.006 --> 08:26.738
It wouldn't help.

08:26.740 --> 08:29.140
Why's that?
All white people look alike?

08:29.142 --> 08:32.744
Yeah, you're all pale,
freckled, and fat.

08:32.746 --> 08:33.545
(LAUGHS)

08:33.547 --> 08:35.647
Satoshi, do you have a problem
with your temper?

08:35.649 --> 08:39.918
I am the victim of this crime.
I was attacked, not him.

08:39.920 --> 08:44.523
But you must have a theory
as to why he attacked you.

08:44.525 --> 08:46.424
Prejudice, maybe?

08:49.663 --> 08:52.430
He's lying. He knew the guy.
We just gotta prove it.

08:52.432 --> 08:54.900
I don't know, witnesses saw
the end of the fight.

08:54.902 --> 08:55.767
They back up
what he's saying.

08:55.769 --> 08:58.503
He pushed the guy, guy hit
his head on the way down.

08:58.505 --> 09:00.338
Could be self-defense.

09:00.574 --> 09:02.240
Anyway, thanks.

09:03.243 --> 09:05.176
I'll take it
from here.

09:09.516 --> 09:11.116
VICKERY: <i> Whoa.</i>

09:11.418 --> 09:13.785
Wow. This is choice.

09:14.788 --> 09:16.321
(VICKERY LAUGHS)

09:16.323 --> 09:19.190
Yeah, I can really feel
the woman's touch, my man.

09:19.192 --> 09:21.026
I would've gone
with higher ceilings,

09:21.028 --> 09:22.727
but your house.

09:22.729 --> 09:24.763
Okay...
(CLEARS THROAT)

09:25.799 --> 09:28.033
So should I use
a doily or...

09:28.035 --> 09:30.835
Can we not talk
while we do this?

09:31.705 --> 09:33.071
Yeah.

09:36.977 --> 09:38.743
Little light reading?

09:41.682 --> 09:42.914
Okay.

09:47.754 --> 09:50.322
First thing they'll do
is a medical evaluation,

09:50.324 --> 09:53.058
make sure the baby
isn't sick or malnourished.

09:53.060 --> 09:55.060
Then they can
hold him for 72 hours

09:55.062 --> 09:57.195
while the
County Child Welfare Board

09:57.197 --> 09:59.564
decide whether
to involve the courts.

09:59.566 --> 10:03.001
If they do,
it could be months.

10:03.003 --> 10:05.537
Throw some law
on them, Kenny-Ken.

10:05.539 --> 10:06.905
Get my Valentine home.

10:06.907 --> 10:07.839
KEN:
It's not that easy.

10:07.841 --> 10:12.444
You need to prove
he's in a safe environment.

10:13.347 --> 10:14.546
What can I do?

10:14.548 --> 10:16.514
Do your folks
live nearby?

10:17.184 --> 10:18.049
They live in Wisconsin.

10:18.051 --> 10:20.785
If you can prove you've got
a support system in place,

10:20.787 --> 10:25.523
that will go a long way.
Otherwise, I'm sorry.

10:27.628 --> 10:28.927
Fuck.

10:37.771 --> 10:39.404
We gotta talk.

10:39.606 --> 10:40.405
No more threats.

10:40.407 --> 10:43.241
It's not a threat.
It's a bargain.

10:43.644 --> 10:45.944
You gotta
start paying your way,

10:45.946 --> 10:48.346
same as everyone else.

10:48.482 --> 10:52.651
Same as sweet Emma.
Unless you wanna get.

10:52.653 --> 10:56.221
No, no.
I thought not.

10:56.223 --> 10:59.557
CHARLIE: <i> You're blooming </i>
<i> in the desert, Kenny.</i>

10:59.559 --> 11:01.993
EMMA: Come with us
to the welfare office.

11:01.995 --> 11:04.729
You can talk
anyone into anything.

11:06.233 --> 11:12.137
I don't want to take a child
from his parents, but this?

11:13.674 --> 11:15.340
It's not safe here.

11:16.309 --> 11:19.911
If you could
convince Mary to...
To leave?

11:19.913 --> 11:21.613
If she told
the welfare board

11:21.615 --> 11:22.714
she wanted to take her son

11:22.716 --> 11:24.949
to her parents,
they'd let her.

11:26.653 --> 11:29.054
The baby
is Charlie's.

11:46.006 --> 11:48.940
Oh, that's a nice one.
You should take it.

11:48.942 --> 11:51.776
Feels like this was
someone else's life.

11:52.379 --> 11:54.145
You still have Emma.

11:54.581 --> 11:56.548
Of course.
You're right.

12:00.420 --> 12:02.020
What are you
looking for?

12:02.022 --> 12:03.421
Signs of life.

12:03.423 --> 12:06.357
Ken fired our housekeeper
and our gardener

12:06.359 --> 12:08.359
over the phone,
two months ago.

12:08.495 --> 12:10.995
None of our friends
have heard from him.

12:11.398 --> 12:12.964
Are you worried?

12:13.066 --> 12:15.133
He's still my husband.

12:16.002 --> 12:17.502
For how long?

12:17.504 --> 12:18.937
You sound like my father.

12:18.939 --> 12:21.773
"You are young
and still beautiful."

12:21.775 --> 12:23.374
You think
he's wrong?

12:23.376 --> 12:26.678
I don't want to stay
in your rental forever,

12:27.748 --> 12:30.081
but I'm not ready
to get remarried.

12:30.951 --> 12:33.418
There's an open seat
on the city council.

12:33.420 --> 12:36.888
Robert Culpepper was named the
interim police commissioner.

12:36.890 --> 12:38.323
I can't afford
a campaign.

12:38.325 --> 12:41.659
Oh, it's not an election,
it's an appointment.

12:44.197 --> 12:45.296
I can't.

12:45.298 --> 12:49.601
My father is supporting me.
He would be furious.

12:49.603 --> 12:51.202
Believe me, I know plenty of

12:51.204 --> 12:53.538
rich lawyers with
political ambitions.

12:53.540 --> 12:56.908
All insufferable,
potbellied, and balding.

12:56.910 --> 12:59.878
You can have your pick.
You can have mine.

12:59.880 --> 13:01.813
Spend the rest
of your life ignored

13:01.815 --> 13:05.216
except for the five minutes
a week he's on top of you.

13:05.218 --> 13:06.251
Becky.

13:06.253 --> 13:11.556
The girl in the photo,
who hasn't been hurt yet.

13:12.893 --> 13:14.425
What would she do?

13:25.071 --> 13:26.905
(HISSING)

13:30.510 --> 13:31.976
Vick.

13:32.479 --> 13:34.946
I think this was
cut with something.

13:35.982 --> 13:37.482
VICKERY: <i> Bri.</i>

13:37.484 --> 13:41.786
<i> Man, I think you might</i>
<i> be right.</i> (SNICKERING)

13:42.722 --> 13:43.922
<i> Oh.</i>

13:44.424 --> 13:46.891
<i> Baby spilled.</i>
(LAUGHING)

13:47.828 --> 13:51.496
<i> I think there's something</i>
<i> seriously wrong with him.</i>

13:51.865 --> 13:53.331
<i> ...Tet Offensive.</i>

13:53.333 --> 13:53.932
<i> Army officials pin</i>

13:53.934 --> 13:59.170
<i> the collapse on his failings</i>
<i> as a man and as a husband.</i>

14:02.509 --> 14:03.975
He needs our help.

14:03.977 --> 14:07.212
I don't think he knows
what he's doing without us.

14:08.882 --> 14:11.749
Look. He thinks
he's alive.

14:20.093 --> 14:23.528
Come on, baby.
He'll show you how.

14:23.530 --> 14:26.598
BRIAN: Oh, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

14:30.270 --> 14:33.738
VICKERY: Get more
on your level, you know.

14:34.274 --> 14:35.940
(VICKERY LAUGHING)

14:35.942 --> 14:37.108
No.

14:40.580 --> 14:41.312
We have to look rich.

14:41.314 --> 14:43.715
Something we took
from Dennis', maybe?

14:47.454 --> 14:48.486
What's wrong?

14:48.488 --> 14:51.356
Charlie already thinks
I'm a terrible mother.

14:51.358 --> 14:52.523
He loves you.

14:52.525 --> 14:54.592
He doesn't
talk to me.

14:54.828 --> 14:59.597
He hasn't been with me since
Sadie brought us Valentine.

14:59.599 --> 15:02.000
Look,
you can't be jealous.

15:02.435 --> 15:06.571
We share everything.
Especially Charlie.

15:06.740 --> 15:08.706
You don't have to share.

15:09.376 --> 15:13.878
Charlie's punishing me
because his son,

15:13.880 --> 15:18.283
his real son died
and it's my fault.

15:19.552 --> 15:20.685
What your dad said,

15:20.687 --> 15:23.221
about going
to live with my parents?

15:23.990 --> 15:25.757
I've thought about it...

15:26.159 --> 15:28.593
About going in
the middle of the night,

15:29.396 --> 15:31.095
not telling anyone.

15:31.564 --> 15:34.933
Please don't.
I need you here.

15:36.102 --> 15:37.568
You barely see me.

15:37.570 --> 15:41.039
Please.
Promise you won't.

15:41.041 --> 15:43.141
I'm sorry, I didn't...
EMMA:
Oh, no, that's okay.

15:43.143 --> 15:44.709
Nothing to hide here.

15:44.711 --> 15:45.576
Um...

15:45.578 --> 15:46.945
Which do you
like better?

15:46.947 --> 15:48.913
The... The one
you're wearing.

15:49.683 --> 15:50.782
Why?

15:50.784 --> 15:57.021
My son got taken from me
by the County Welfare Board.

15:57.857 --> 16:00.425
Is there anything
I could do to help?

16:01.294 --> 16:03.594
We need to look rich.

16:05.899 --> 16:06.431
Hey, Meg?

16:06.433 --> 16:09.834
She's not working today.
Do you need something?

16:09.836 --> 16:11.736
Yeah, Lyons' vic.
I need a name.

16:11.738 --> 16:13.838
It's not in the file?
I don't have a file.

16:13.840 --> 16:15.206
Because it's not
your case.

16:15.208 --> 16:16.341
And now we're back to the

16:16.343 --> 16:18.343
beginning of
the question, yes.

16:18.411 --> 16:19.978
I'll get you a copy.
Oh, ah, ah...

16:19.980 --> 16:21.913
I also need some
personal history,

16:21.915 --> 16:25.383
anything you can find,
background with the doer.

16:50.243 --> 16:51.843
CHARLIE: Terry Melcher.

16:51.845 --> 16:52.844
(TERRY CHUCKLES)

16:52.846 --> 16:55.546
CHARLIE: Yeah.
Ferrari in the shop?

16:55.548 --> 16:57.682
TERRY: (CHUCKLES)
Yeah.

16:59.652 --> 17:01.552
Didn't expect
to see you out here, man.

17:01.554 --> 17:03.221
Yeah, well,
we had a deal, Charlie.

17:03.223 --> 17:06.391
I'm here to record your songs,
like I promised.

17:06.760 --> 17:09.927
Well, hell yes, you are.
